nted tastes and smells have transformed water into a highly industrialized food product divorced from its origins. The Taste of Water invites readers to question their own assumptions about what water does and should naturally taste like while exposing them to the invisible—but substantial—sensory labor involved in creating tap water.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aDrinking waterxSensory evaluationzFrancey20th century. 0aDrinking waterxSensory evaluationzUnited Statesy20th century. 0aMunicipal water supplyzFrancey20th century. 0aMunicipal water supplyzUnited Statesy20th century. 0aWaterxPurificationxTaste and odor controlzFrancey20th century. 0aWaterxPurificationxTaste and odor controlzUnited Statesy20th century. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520393561?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520393561423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520393561/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles